## a complete guide for all language/translation management scenarios:

Language & Translation Management Guide
Overview of Data Model
Each translation document has these fields:
{
languageCode: string; // "en", "es", "hi", etc.
namespace: string; // "common", "auth", "attendance", etc.
key: string; // e.g., "save", "login.button"
value: string; // e.g., "Guardar"
platforms: string[]; // ["mobile"], ["web"], or ["mobile", "web"]
updatedBy: string | null;
}

---

Case 1: Fresh Database - Add Languages + Translations
Scenario: You deleted the entire database and want to rebuild everything.
Step 1: Start Backend (Auto-creates Languages)
cd crewroster-backend
npm run start:dev
This automatically runs ensureLanguagesExist() which creates:

- en (English) - default
- es (Spanish)
- gu-en (Gujarati-English)
  Step 2: Seed Translations from Static JSON Files
  npm run seed:translations
  Output shows:
  en: mobile 289 keys, web 256 keys → 440 total
  es: mobile 289 keys, web 256 keys → 440 total  
  gu-en: mobile 289 keys, web 426 keys → 559 total
  The script automatically:
- Merges mobile + web translations
- Tags keys found in both as platforms: ['mobile', 'web']
- Tags mobile-only as platforms: ['mobile']
- Tags web-only as platforms: ['web']

